                            <body>
                                <p> LAGOS, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Australian Prime Minister John  Howard said on Monday he had expressed to Nigerian President  Olusegun Obasanjo his concern over the case of a mother  sentenced to death by stoning for adultery.</p>
                                <p> A Nigerian court last month rejected an appeal by Amina  Lawal Kurami against her conviction for bearing a child out of  wedlock and confirmed her sentence under Islamic sharia law,  drawing a barrage of international criticism.</p>
                                <p> Howard, in Nigeria as chair of a special Commonwealth  committee on Zimbabwe, said on the sidelines of talks in Abuja  that he had already outlined his fears about the fate of the  31-year-old in a letter to Obasanjo.</p>
                                <p> "I had already raised it in a letter and I raised it  personally in my discussion with President Obasanjo last night,"  Radio Australia quoted Howard as saying.</p>
                                <p> The report said Howard spent almost an hour with the  Nigerian president discussing what he said was an important  case.</p>
                                <p> Kurami was sentenced to death in March by a lower court in  her state of Katsina, which like a number of others in northern  Nigeria has adopted strict Islamic sharia law.</p>
                                <p> She was granted a two-year reprieve to wean her  eight-month-old baby and would not be stoned until 2004.</p>
                                <p> The adoption of sharia law has polarised Nigeria, Africa's  most populous nation, whose population of over 120 million is  almost evenly divided between Christians and Muslims.</p>
                                <p> More than 3,000 people have died in religious clashes in the  past two years in the traditionally secular west Africa country.</p>
                                <p> Kurami is the second woman to be sentenced to death for  bearing a child outside marriage since 2000, when sharia law was  first adopted in Nigeria.</p>
                                <p> In March, an appeals court quashed a similar sentence on  Safiya Hussaini Tungar-Tudu after worldwide appeals for  clemency.</p>
                                <p> Last month, another Muslim court in central Niger state  sentenced a pregnant woman and her lover to be stoned to death  after convicting them for adultery.    </p>
